thread.title: Boivin: Odd Pac-12 season could help ASU
thread.title_full: Boivin: Odd Pac-12 season could help ASU

author: azcentral.com
title: Boivin: Odd Pac-12 season could help ASU
text:
The ball was passed. The ball was tipped. The ball was airborne. The ball was caught. The ball was in the end zone.
That was a scoring play for Arizona State in the third quarter Saturday against Colorado. It also summed up a 2015 Pac-12 football season filled with misdirections, imperfections and even a bit of indiscretion (we’re talking about you, Steve Sarkisian).
ASU’s 48-23 victory at Sun Devil Stadium means it remains in the mix to win the South. More answers will come next weekend in Salt Lake City but for now the Sun Devils should feel good about being relevant again.
An upset of No. 7 UCLA and a domination of Colorado will do that for you.
"Doesn't matter where you start, don't matter where you are in the middle, it matters where you finish," ASU coach Todd Graham said.
AZCENTRAL
ASU XTRA app: Get latest news, analysis, scores, photos
Here’s something the Sun Devils should feel good about: Graham is 25-11 in his career in November, including 14-3 at home. And if it sounds crazy to talk about ASU’s possibilities in the long-term after the debacle against USC two weeks ago, keep in mind the unpredictability of this conference works to the team’s favor.
And by unpredictably I mean unimpressiveness.
Take the Trojans. They regularly grab the top recruits in the country. They have at least four players who will be selected in the NFL draft after the season. Yet they are coming off a 17-12 loss to Washington and have games against Notre Dame, Utah and California up next.
Oregon fell to Washington State Saturday. Washington State. At home. Yes, the Cougars are improved but this is the same team that fell to Portland State to open their schedule.
Before the season, Oregon, USC, UCLA, Arizona State, Stanford and Arizona were in the Top 25 preseason poll. Only three of those six remain and more could fall.
Utah was the only one in the Top 10 this week, while No. 20 Stanford had to claw its way back up the polls after losing its season-opener to Northwestern.
It’s hard to imagine a Pac-12 team representing the conference in the College Football Playoffs. Too much league cannibalism.
AZCENTRAL
Arizona State gets key breaks, runs away from Colorado
ASU fans should consider that good news.
"We're six games into this thing and we have six left," Graham said. "If we can win all six of them, then that's exactly where you want to be. We control our own destiny."
One of Graham's strength is his ability to keep players focused during a long and emotionally trying season. Each year he has helped his team rebound from an early tough loss. Of course his next big hurdle for the future: Avoid the early tough loss.
But after a slow start, the Sun Devils are finding their way.
Wide receivers are improved, linemen are healthy and the offense has turned the corner, often while stiff-arming the opponent.
On Saturday, quarterback Mike Bercovici threw five touchdown passes, tying his career high, and completed 20 of 31 passes for 260 yards and one interception.
With Jaelen Strong of the Houston Texas watching from the sidelines, Tim White emerged as a true go-to threat with seven catches for 144 yards.
It was White's second of two touchdowns that reflected how crazy ASU's season has become.
It was fourth and two at the Colorado 45 when Graham had a conversation with offensive coordinator Mike Norvell about what to do.
"I guarantee you this play's going to work," Norvell told him.
It did, but only after Bercovici's pass was deflected by Buffaloes cornerback Ahkello Witherspoon. White took it 45 yards for the touchdown.
"I was just about to get a little upset," Graham said. "But it worked out. ... Our guys are hustling and making things happen there. So you work hard and you play every play and max out every play, good things happen to you. Sometimes it bounces your way."
The defense dominated early but also revealed a propensity for giving up big plays. Colorado’s receivers had catches of 68, 67 and 42 yards, the price a defense will pay when it blitzes often.
Still, it will be a topic of discussion during practice this week as the Sun Devils prepare for their most important conference game of the season so far. The Utes have done an impressive job becoming a football power during their short time in the Pac-12.
It will be a test but the good news for ASU is that Graham has the best conference record (21-9) among Pac-12 South teams since he's been in Tempe.
AZCENTRAL
Analysis from ASU's win over Colorado
ASU set a tone of focus and efficiency early, and even when things went wrong they went right.
During their first possession, the Sun Devils drove to the Colorado 30 before Demario Richard fumbled. Fortunately for him, tight end Kody Kohl scooped it up and ran 28 yards for the touchdown.
The defense kept up the momentum when safety Kareem Orr intercepted Sefo Liufau. Five plays later, Bercovici found Kohl for a four-yard scoring pass and the Sun Devils quickly went up 14-0.
Phillip Lindsay’s 16-yard touchdown run closed the Buffaloes to within seven but White worked his magic, catching 38- and 45-yard touchdown passes from Bercovici, who has become the deep ball threat many expected him to be this season.
Bercovici also had seven carries and averaged 5.7 yards.
AZCENTRAL
ASU sharpens focus amid wide-open Pac-12 South
"We're moving onto next week already," Bercovici said. "Our mentality is to enjoy the win for 15 minutes, and already our mentality is to go 1-0 against Utah.
.
Bercovici likes where his team is.
"I think if you were to ask would we want to switch the situation we are in right now, I would say no, because we have dealt with adversity, we are excited about the situation, we are more hungry now that we do have those two losses and we have already moved passed it," he said.
If this season is anything like Graham's career here, the future looks promising. He started out 5-5 his first season, which included a four-game losing streak.
He is 27-9 since.
